2.798J | Molecular, Cellular and Tissue Biomechanics (BE.410J) | http://ocw.mit.edu/courses/biological-engineering/20-410j-molecular-cellular-and-tissue-biomechanics-be-410j-spring-2003 | textbook:Daune, Michel. Chapter 2 in Molecular Biophysics. New York, NY: Oxford University Press, 1999. textbook:Dill, K. A., and S. Bromberg. Chapters 6, 8 and 10 in Molecular Driving Forces. New York, NY: Routledge, 2002. textbook:Boal, David H. Chapter 2 in Mechanics of the Cell. Cambridge, UK: Cambridge University Press, 2002. textbook:Howard, Johnathon. Chapters 5 and 10 in Mechanics of Motor Proteins and the Cytoskeleton. Sunderland, MA: Sinauer Associates, 2001. textbook:Ward, J. P. Solid Mechanics. New York, NY: Springer, 1992. textbook:Lodish, H., et. al. Molecular Cell Biology. 3rd. ed. New York, NY: Scientific American Books/W.H. Freeman, 1995. textbook:Malvern, Lawrence E. Chapter 6 in Introduction to the Mechanics of a Continuous Medium. Englewood Cliffs, N.J.: Prentice-Hall, 1969, pp. 278-282. textbook:Fung, Y. C. Biomechanics: Mechanical Properties of Living Tissues. New York, NY: Springer-Verlag, 1993. textbook:Ferry, J. D. "The Nature of Viscoelastic Behavior." Chapter 1 in Viscoelastic Properties of Polymers. New York, NY: Wiley, 1980. level:Graduate instructors:Roger D. Kamm,  Patrick Doyle,  Maxine Jonas<br/>(Teaching Assistant) term:Spring 2003 features:Lecture notes, Assignments (no solutions), Exams (no solutions) description:This course develops and applies scaling laws and the methods of continuum mechanics to biomechanical phenomena over a range of length scales. Topics include: structure of tissues and the molecular basis for macroscopic properties; chemical and electrical effects on mechanical behavior; cell mechanics, motility and adhesion; biomembranes; biomolecular mechanics and molecular motors. Experimental methods for probing structures at the tissue, cellular, and molecular levels will also be investigated.This course was originally co-developed by Professors Alan Grodzinsky, Roger Kamm, and L. Mahadevan.
